stdyInfo.abstract: Topics addressed in this study include World Trade Center terrorist attacks, rating of George Bush as president, direction of the country, concerns about the future, importance of career components, likelihood of starting a business, vehicles for financial security, most important thing that would improve respondent's life, availability of information, and marketing strategies to gain information about customer's personal preferences. Demographic variables include respondent's gender, year of birth, age category, marital status, employment status, starting salary after college, profession, educational status, ownership of a non-retirement investment account, country or region of residence, state of residence, zip code, hours per week spent on the Internet or World Wide Web, type of Internet connection and browser used, sexual orientation, origin or descent (Spanish, Hispanic, or Latino), race, number of individuals under age 18 and number 18 or over living in the household, age of each child under age 18, household income before taxes, and household's total investable assets.

method.notes: National cross-sectional sample of recent college graduates.

stdyInfo.abstract: "Topics addressed in this study include the most important issues for the government to address, 2004 presidential election, ratings of political leaders, favor keeping troops in Iraq or bringing most of our troops home in the next year, effect of the invasion of Iraq on the war on terrorism, accuracy of the U.S. government's reports of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction and links to Al Qaeda, the Alienation Index which measures feelings of powerlessness and isolation, and work and leisure activities. method.notes: National cross-sectional sample of persons 18 years of age or older interviewed by telephone.

stdyInfo.abstract:
Respondents were asked their preference for bus, train, car or plane transportation for trips of 100 miles or more and the factors that influenced this choice, such as cost, comfort, convenience, flexibility, speed, terminal location, and energy efficiency.

Indepth questions about train service include use of Amtrak, government funding for improvements, public image, quality of food and service, safety, baggage and reservation handling, affect of cost, location, and condition of train stations.

method.notes: Harris obtained a cross-section sample of the U.S. population 18 years and over. Attitudes on various topics were collected by questionnaire in a telephone interview; U.S. adults 18 years and over

titlStmt.titl: Harris 1985 Business-Week survey on computer and office automation purchases, no. 851207

stdyInfo.abstract:
This survey among corporate EDP administrators focuses on the decision-making process for buying or leasing computers and computer- related products

"Variables included estimates of purchases or cutbacks in EDP equipment; support from 'top management'; increased productivity; automation of production; and main considerations when purchasing EDP equipment"

method.notes: Harris telephone surveys use a form of random digit dialing. Additional sampling information for this special sample of business leaders was not provided

distStmt.distrbtr: Louis Harris Data Center, University of North Carolina

stdyInfo.abstract: Two samples (general public 18-64 years of age and people over 65) were questioned about their perceptions of aging, retirement, leisure time and how it feels to be over 65.

method.notes: Harris used a random multi-stage cluster sampling design to obtain a national cross-section sample of the U.S. population 18 years and over. A cross-section of people over 65 was also collected. Attitudes on various topics related to aging were collected in a face-to-face interview; "U.S. adults, 18 years and over; adults over 65."

stdyInfo.abstract:
Survey conducted three days prior to the 1972 presidential elections focuses on voter attitudes toward certain key issues.

Questions include intention to vote, reason for preference for George McGovern or Richard Nixon, possible Vietnam peace settlement, and cost of living.

method.notes: Harris used a random multi-stage cluster sampling design to obtain a national cross-section sample of likely voters. Attitudes on various topics were collected by questionnaire in a face-to-face interview; U.S. adults, likely voters

stdyInfo.abstract:
Pre-election survey investigates reasons for preferences for Richard Nixon or George McGovern for president.

Additional questions focus on the economy, inflation, recession, unemployment, Wage-Price Control Board, break-in at Democratic National Headquarters, and legitimacy of wiretapping.

method.notes: Harris used a random multi-stage cluster sampling design to obtain a national cross-section sample of likely voters. Attitudes on various topics were collected by questionnaire in a face-to-face interview; U.S. adults, likely voters

stdyInfo.abstract: This study attempts to identify challenges and opportunities facing black women leaders. Questions were asked on confidence in institutions, factors contributing to motivation, requirements for achieving and holding power, dealing with opposition, and attitudes toward black women in the workplace.

method.notes: This study utilized face-to-face and telephone interviews with a specific number of persons in seven leadership categories (business leaders, top federal officials, governors, mayors, black business leaders, black leadership forum, and black women leaders). The results of this survey are qualitative and are not statistically significant.
